CMake is a mature utility for building software projects. CMake works by generating [makefiles | build system] for the host machine from platform and compiler independent configuration files that describe the [build process | compilation procedure | build system], rather than script it.
Setting up and compiling GCHP is somewhat involved (especially first-time)
Environment needs to be configured properly
Troubleshooting errors is difficult without expert knowledge
Compiler logs are hard to understand
GCHP sometimes requires hard-coded modifications to Makefiles
Maintaining the build system takes considerable effort
Makefiles naturally form a monolithic system – one build systems that compiles all requisite components
Each component – typically developed by different developers – has it’s own configuration (flags, variables, paths) and subcomponents
